    abstract="An optimization problem is the task of minimizing (or maximizing --- for definiteness we discuss minimization) a certain real-valued ``objective functional'' (or ``cost'' , or ``energy'' , or ``performance index'', etc.) E(x), possibly under a set of equality and/or inequality constraints, where x = (x1, {\ldots}, xn) is a vector (often the discretization of one or several functions) of unknown variables (real or complex numbers, and/or integers, and/or Ising spins, etc.). A general process for solving such problems is the point-by-point minimization, in which one changes only one variable xj(or few of them) at a time, lowering E as much as possible in each such step. More generally, the process accepts any candidate change of one or few variables if it causes a drop in energy (бE < 0).",
